32: /**
33:  * This {@link AllocationDecider} controls shard allocation based on
34:  * {@code awareness} key-value pairs defined in the node configuration.
35:  * Awareness explicitly controls where replicas should be allocated based on
36:  * attributes like node or physical rack locations. Awareness attributes accept
37:  * arbitrary configuration keys like a rack data-center identifier. For example
38:  * the setting:
39:  * <pre>
40:  * cluster.routing.allocation.awareness.attributes: rack_id
41:  * </pre>
42:  * <p>
43:  * will cause allocations to be distributed over different racks such that
44:  * ideally at least one replicas of the all shard is available on the same rack.
45:  * To enable allocation awareness in this example nodes should contain a value
46:  * for the {@code rack_id} key like:
47:  * <pre>
48:  * node.attr.rack_id:1
49:  * </pre>
50:  * <p>
51:  * Awareness can also be used to prevent over-allocation in the case of node or
52:  * even "zone" failure. For example in cloud-computing infrastructures like
53:  * Amazon AWS a cluster might span over multiple "zones". Awareness can be used
54:  * to distribute replicas to individual zones by setting:
55:  * <pre>
56:  * cluster.routing.allocation.awareness.attributes: zone
57:  * </pre>
58:  * <p>
59:  * and forcing allocation to be aware of the following zone the data resides in:
60:  * <pre>
61:  * cluster.routing.allocation.awareness.force.zone.values: zone1,zone2
62:  * </pre>
63:  * <p>
64:  * In contrast to regular awareness this setting will prevent over-allocation on
65:  * {@code zone1} even if {@code zone2} fails partially or becomes entirely
66:  * unavailable. Nodes that belong to a certain zone / group should be started
67:  * with the zone id configured on the node-level settings like:
68:  * <pre>
69:  * node.zone: zone1
70:  * </pre>
71:  */
